00:22:36,825 --> 00:22:41,030
♪ Come on the peace train ♪

520
00:22:45,033 --> 00:22:49,238
♪ Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah ♪

521
00:22:52,040 --> 00:22:55,605
[LAUGHS] Oh, I must call Kennedy.

522
00:22:55,610 --> 00:22:56,610
At once.

523
00:22:56,615 --> 00:22:57,975
He and I are brothers,

524
00:22:57,980 --> 00:23:00,911
just like... just like
you and I are brothers.

525
00:23:00,916 --> 00:23:03,714
- Yes!
- We are all humans

526
00:23:03,719 --> 00:23:06,717
placed on this one, fragile planet.

527
00:23:06,722 --> 00:23:10,087
And the only way forward is...

528
00:23:10,092 --> 00:23:12,022
love!

529
00:23:12,027 --> 00:23:13,123
[LAUGHS]

530
00:23:13,128 --> 00:23:15,225
<i>[HOPEFUL MUSIC]</i>

531
00:23:15,230 --> 00:23:18,562
[ALIEN ROARING]

532
00:23:18,567 --> 00:23:21,732
<i>[TENSE MUSIC]</i>

533
00:23:21,737 --> 00:23:22,895
<i>♪ ♪</i>

534
00:23:22,900 --> 00:23:23,900
How about another tune?

535
00:23:23,905 --> 00:23:25,469
I told you that thing

536
00:23:25,474 --> 00:23:26,670
was sent to kill me!

537
00:23:26,675 --> 00:23:29,272
If it's war the Americans want,

538
00:23:29,277 --> 00:23:31,579
it's war they shall have!

539
00:23:33,381 --> 00:23:37,147
Prepare the missile
for launch immediately!

540
00:23:37,152 --> 00:23:39,687
<i>♪ ♪</i>

541
00:23:42,259 --> 00:23:43,259
[GROANS]

542
00:23:43,264 --> 00:23:45,629
Oh, damn it.

543
00:23:45,634 --> 00:23:48,298
We forgot Behrad. Again.

544
00:23:48,303 --> 00:23:50,700
[GROWLS] Sí!

545
00:23:50,705 --> 00:23:52,434
Guys, thought you might like

546
00:23:52,438 --> 00:23:54,135
a little update on El Comandante.

547
00:23:54,140 --> 00:23:56,737
Wait, you're with Fidel Castro?

548
00:23:56,742 --> 00:23:58,739
Yeah, we're super tight,
but the problem is,

549
00:23:58,744 --> 00:24:00,342
he thinks the alien
was sent to kill him.

550
00:24:00,346 --> 00:24:02,844
- Why would he think that?
- Because it tried to kill him.

551
00:24:02,849 --> 00:24:04,245
Report back to me

552
00:24:04,250 --> 00:24:06,380
as soon as the missile has been fueled.

553
00:24:06,385 --> 00:24:07,849
Oh, and also, he's preparing

554
00:24:07,854 --> 00:24:10,518
to launch a nuclear missile at D.C.

555
00:24:10,523 --> 00:24:12,219
Why does Castro have a nuke?

556
00:24:12,224 --> 00:24:14,755
'Cause we gave it to him.

557
00:24:14,760 --> 00:24:16,023
You said "no shooting".

558
00:24:16,028 --> 00:24:18,226
I said... oh, my God.

559
00:24:18,231 --> 00:24:19,894
Oh, my God, this is not happening.

560
00:24:19,899 --> 00:24:22,463
Oh, God. Okay, okay, okay.

561
00:24:22,468 --> 00:24:23,765
Let's just hope that cooler heads

562
00:24:23,769 --> 00:24:25,670
are prevailing in D.C., right?

563
00:24:29,508 --> 00:24:31,639
One of our boys flying over Cuba

564
00:24:31,644 --> 00:24:33,708
reports a missile being fueled.

565
00:24:33,713 --> 00:24:35,243
Has Khrushchev lost his mind?

566
00:24:35,248 --> 00:24:37,044
It would appear that
the missile is no longer

567
00:24:37,049 --> 00:24:38,746
in the Soviets' possession, sir.

568
00:24:38,751 --> 00:24:41,249
[LAUGHS] Castro's got it.

569
00:24:41,254 --> 00:24:44,151
History is not supposed
to go down like this.

570
00:24:44,156 --> 00:24:46,721
<i>[TENSE MUSIC]</i>

571
00:24:46,726 --> 00:24:48,189
Say there, Jackie,

572
00:24:48,194 --> 00:24:50,291
how would you and the
kids feel about, uh,

573
00:24:50,296 --> 00:24:52,393
getting out of town for a couple days?

574
00:24:52,398 --> 00:24:55,830
Uh, I think Jack's starting to crack.

575
00:24:55,835 --> 00:24:57,365
Does anyone know if Hyannis Port

576
00:24:57,370 --> 00:24:58,600
is within the blast radius?

577
00:24:58,605 --> 00:25:00,802
There is no time for
this, Mr. President!

578
00:25:00,807 --> 00:25:03,805
If those Russkies catch us
blinking now, we're through!

579
00:25:03,810 --> 00:25:06,107
What if this is just
a big misunderstanding?

580
00:25:06,112 --> 00:25:08,876
What if those Russkies
want us to hit Cuba

581
00:25:08,881 --> 00:25:10,578
so they can hit us?

582
00:25:10,583 --> 00:25:12,651
Those clever Commie bastards!

583
00:25:14,220 --> 00:25:18,085
Our only defense is to attack the USSR!

584
00:25:18,090 --> 00:25:20,288
Jack, that is insane.

585
00:25:20,293 --> 00:25:23,524
<i>♪ ♪</i>

586
00:25:23,529 --> 00:25:25,230
Take us to DEFCON 2.

587
00:25:27,300 --> 00:25:28,633
Yes, sir.

588
00:25:33,639 --> 00:25:36,074
Sir, maybe I can help.

589
00:25:38,701 --> 00:25:41,499
My secretary can type
120 words a minute.

590
00:25:41,504 --> 00:25:44,879
This way, we could get the
bombers in the air faster.

591
00:25:44,884 --> 00:25:47,049
And here I thought you were
just another pretty face.

592
00:25:47,053 --> 00:25:48,316
[CHUCKLES] Oh, gosh.

593
00:25:48,321 --> 00:25:49,750
There you go.

594
00:25:49,755 --> 00:25:52,486
[CLEARS THROAT]

595
00:25:52,491 --> 00:25:54,155
This is a direct order

596
00:25:54,160 --> 00:25:56,237
from the President of the United States

597
00:25:56,242 --> 00:25:58,492
to the entire Strategic Air Command.

598
00:25:58,497 --> 00:26:01,695
I've never seen someone type
with just their thumbs before.

599
00:26:01,700 --> 00:26:04,765
I want every B-52 we
have headed towards

600
00:26:04,770 --> 00:26:07,034
their primary targets
in the Soviet Union.

601
00:26:07,039 --> 00:26:10,604
Should we lose contact due
to a first strike from Cuba,

602
00:26:10,609 --> 00:26:14,809
it should be considered a
direct attack from the USSR.

603
00:26:14,814 --> 00:26:17,144
Full retaliatory measures
must then be taken

604
00:26:17,149 --> 00:26:18,950
without any further orders.

605
00:26:21,587 --> 00:26:23,384
Because we'll all be dead.

606
00:26:23,389 --> 00:26:27,394
<i>♪ ♪</i>

607
00:26:27,960 --> 00:26:29,890
Did you get all that, sweetie?

608
00:26:29,895 --> 00:26:33,231
Oh, every last word, sir. [CHUCKLES]

609
00:26:35,067 --> 00:26:38,098
Guys, why is Fidel
starting World War III?

610
00:26:38,103 --> 00:26:40,901
Because he thinks you guys
are invading Cuba with aliens.

611
00:26:40,906 --> 00:26:43,437
Look, Behrad's trying to cool him down.

612
00:26:43,442 --> 00:26:45,373
Comandante.

613
00:26:45,378 --> 00:26:47,108
You have a phone call.

614
00:26:47,113 --> 00:26:48,943
It's Che Guevara.

615
00:26:48,948 --> 00:26:51,545
Hello, old friend.

616
00:26:51,550 --> 00:26:53,247
Yes, I know.

617
00:26:53,252 --> 00:26:56,417
The news is very scary at the moment.

618
00:26:56,422 --> 00:26:58,219
[LAUGHS]

619
00:26:58,224 --> 00:27:01,322
Yes, I wish you were here too.

620
00:27:01,327 --> 00:27:04,959
But I have a comrade-in-arms
right next to me

621
00:27:04,964 --> 00:27:08,496
who's the next best thing.

622
00:27:08,501 --> 00:27:12,299
<i>[EXCITING MUSIC]</i>

623
00:27:12,304 --> 00:27:16,270
<i>♪ ♪</i>

624
00:27:16,275 --> 00:27:20,480
Tell the CIA to call back
their squid soldiers,

625
00:27:20,485 --> 00:27:23,183
or else I'll launch the nuke!

626
00:27:23,188 --> 00:27:24,712
Oh, my God.

627
00:27:24,717 --> 00:27:27,982
<i>[TENSE MUSIC]</i>

628
00:27:27,987 --> 00:27:29,917
Okay, sounds like you're up, Rory.

629
00:27:29,922 --> 00:27:31,485
Thought I was in the doghouse.

630
00:27:31,490 --> 00:27:33,455
That's when we were trying
to finesse the situation.

631
00:27:33,459 --> 00:27:35,256
Plans change.

632
00:27:35,261 --> 00:27:36,624
You want us to kill the alien?

633
00:27:36,629 --> 00:27:38,258
We don't have a choice, okay?

634
00:27:38,262 --> 00:27:39,627
Spooner, I need you
to help him track it.

635
00:27:39,631 --> 00:27:40,896
We need to deescalate the situation

636
00:27:40,900 --> 00:27:42,797
and get history back on track.

637
00:27:42,802 --> 00:27:45,031
Screw history! You kill the alien,

638
00:27:45,036 --> 00:27:46,347
you kill any chance of finding Sara.

639
00:27:46,351 --> 00:27:47,801
And if we don't kill it, then Castro

640
00:27:47,806 --> 00:27:48,836
starts a nuclear war,

641
00:27:48,841 --> 00:27:50,467
and Sara doesn't have a
home to return to, okay?

642
00:27:50,471 --> 00:27:53,140
I do not have time to game
this out with you, Rory.

643
00:27:53,145 --> 00:27:54,576
We will find another way to find Sara.

644
00:27:54,580 --> 00:27:57,111
Right. Lot of big brains on this ship.

645
00:27:57,116 --> 00:27:59,246
I'll just stick with what I know.

646
00:27:59,251 --> 00:28:00,781
You should never have cleaned me up.

647
00:28:00,786 --> 00:28:02,217
I'm better off doing what I do best:

648
00:28:02,221 --> 00:28:03,851
being a goon, killing people.

649
00:28:03,856 --> 00:28:05,156
Yes.

650
00:28:06,725 --> 00:28:08,159
That's exactly what I need.

651
00:28:12,431 --> 00:28:13,561
Right.

652
00:28:13,566 --> 00:28:15,696
Least I know what I'm here for.

653
00:28:15,701 --> 00:28:19,906
<i>♪ ♪</i>

654
00:28:23,097 --> 00:28:24,892
- Alien's gone.
<i>- [SHARP RINGING]</i>

655
00:28:24,897 --> 00:28:27,160
No, it's still here, I can sense it.

656
00:28:27,165 --> 00:28:28,562
Base is wide open.

657
00:28:28,567 --> 00:28:30,764
Why would the stupid
thing still be here?

658
00:28:30,769 --> 00:28:34,301
It's not stupid, it's
looking for something.

659
00:28:34,306 --> 00:28:35,604
You know, it wasn't right for Ava

660
00:28:35,608 --> 00:28:37,637
to try to pin this all on you.

661
00:28:37,642 --> 00:28:38,972
I don't give a rat's ass.

662
00:28:38,977 --> 00:28:40,440
You were just trying to find Sara.

663
00:28:40,445 --> 00:28:42,443
No, I was pretending
to be somebody I'm not.

664
00:28:42,447 --> 00:28:44,678
So you're just gonna go back
to being a dumb drunk?

665
00:28:44,683 --> 00:28:46,913
- That it?
- Yes.

666
00:28:46,918 --> 00:28:50,584
<i>[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC]</i>

667
00:28:50,589 --> 00:28:53,353
[ALARM BLARING]

668
00:28:53,358 --> 00:28:54,455
Is that...

669
00:28:54,460 --> 00:28:57,429
[ALIEN GROWLING]

670
00:28:58,797 --> 00:29:01,461
What's it want with the nuke?

671
00:29:01,466 --> 00:29:03,030
I think it wants to get away from here.

672
00:29:03,034 --> 00:29:06,270
Like, off this planet.

673
00:29:07,606 --> 00:29:09,469
Wait here.

674
00:29:09,474 --> 00:29:13,679
<i>♪ ♪</i>

675
00:29:16,014 --> 00:29:17,477
Hey, dummy.

676
00:29:17,482 --> 00:29:19,679
[ALIEN SNARLS]

677
00:29:19,684 --> 00:29:23,049
You really think you're gonna
hitch a ride home on that thing?

678
00:29:23,054 --> 00:29:24,718
[ALIEN CHITTERS]

679
00:29:24,723 --> 00:29:25,785
It's a missile!

680
00:29:25,790 --> 00:29:27,621
[ALIEN ROARING]

681
00:29:27,626 --> 00:29:30,690
[GROANING]

682
00:29:30,695 --> 00:29:32,692
Go ahead, eat me.

683
00:29:32,697 --> 00:29:35,162
But you're not gonna get home.

684
00:29:35,167 --> 00:29:36,396
Let him go!

685
00:29:36,401 --> 00:29:37,664
[ALIEN SNARLS]

686
00:29:37,669 --> 00:29:39,399
I know you understand me.

687
00:29:39,404 --> 00:29:42,269
Put him down, or I blow your ass away.

688
00:29:42,274 --> 00:29:44,871
That thing is not a spaceship.

689
00:29:44,876 --> 00:29:47,874
But lucky for you,

690
00:29:47,879 --> 00:29:49,509
I've got my own.

691
00:29:49,514 --> 00:29:52,012
[ALIEN CHITTERING]

692
00:29:52,017 --> 00:29:53,513
Keep talking.

693
00:29:53,518 --> 00:29:55,316
It understands you. It
just doesn't trust you.

694
00:29:55,320 --> 00:29:57,184
You're not as dumb as you look.

695
00:29:57,189 --> 00:29:59,486
[ALIEN CHITTERING]

696
00:29:59,491 --> 00:30:01,922
The alien wants its own
spaceship, not yours.

697
00:30:01,927 --> 00:30:03,924
[ALIEN CHITTERING]

698
00:30:03,929 --> 00:30:05,559
I can take you to it.

699
00:30:05,564 --> 00:30:08,061
[ALIEN SNARLS]

700
00:30:08,066 --> 00:30:10,063
But under one condition.

701
00:30:10,068 --> 00:30:13,166
You help me find my friend.

702
00:30:13,171 --> 00:30:17,308
[ALIEN ROARING]

703
00:30:20,245 --> 00:30:22,375
She's asking you a question.

704
00:30:22,380 --> 00:30:23,510
She?

705
00:30:23,515 --> 00:30:25,259
Yeah, she wants to know
what kind of fuel

706
00:30:25,264 --> 00:30:27,714
the Waverider uses.

707
00:30:27,719 --> 00:30:30,521
Sounds like we got a long
trip to find the captain.

708
00:30:33,758 --> 00:30:35,388
<i>[TENSE MUSIC]</i>

709
00:30:35,393 --> 00:30:37,290
Comandante, what are you doing?

710
00:30:37,295 --> 00:30:38,692
What does it look like I'm doing?

711
00:30:38,697 --> 00:30:40,093
You will start World War III.

712
00:30:40,098 --> 00:30:43,463
You will kill all of us.

713
00:30:43,468 --> 00:30:45,799
[COMPUTER BEEPS]

714
00:30:45,804 --> 00:30:50,009
<i>♪ ♪</i>

715
00:30:53,178 --> 00:30:57,277
[ALARM BLARING]

716
00:30:57,282 --> 00:31:00,151
History will absolve me.

717
00:31:01,152 --> 00:31:04,388
[ROCKET ENGINE ROARING]

718
00:31:11,263 --> 00:31:14,327
- [COMPUTER BEEPING]
- Call for you, General Kilgore.

719
00:31:14,332 --> 00:31:17,430
Thank me? What for?

720
00:31:17,435 --> 00:31:19,499
What three-day weekend?

721
00:31:19,504 --> 00:31:22,469
And who all received that order?

722
00:31:22,474 --> 00:31:25,805
The entire Strategic Air Command?!

723
00:31:25,810 --> 00:31:28,508
Should've known that she
was too good to be true!

724
00:31:28,513 --> 00:31:31,778
This secretary has been
countermanding your orders, sir,

725
00:31:31,783 --> 00:31:34,147
and if Fidel Castro
launches that missile,

726
00:31:34,152 --> 00:31:35,849
you have only got seven minutes

727
00:31:35,854 --> 00:31:38,285
to order a counterstrike
against the Soviet Union.

728
00:31:38,290 --> 00:31:39,290
But I thought you said

729
00:31:39,295 --> 00:31:41,059
all our B-52s are still on the ground.

730
00:31:41,064 --> 00:31:42,422
Well, as much as it pains me

731
00:31:42,427 --> 00:31:44,428
to have to ask the navy for help...

732
00:31:48,266 --> 00:31:49,729
What is that?

733
00:31:49,734 --> 00:31:51,534
That is the nuclear football.

734
00:31:51,539 --> 00:31:54,234
Sir, that allows you to contact

735
00:31:54,239 --> 00:31:56,770
the nuclear submarine captains directly

736
00:31:56,775 --> 00:31:59,839
and order an all-out strike
against the Soviets.

737
00:31:59,844 --> 00:32:02,842
Jack, they don't want a nuclear war

738
00:32:02,847 --> 00:32:04,548
any more than you do.

739
00:32:05,984 --> 00:32:09,520
[TELETYPE CLACKING]

740
00:32:13,158 --> 00:32:15,689
There's been a report of
a missile launch from Cuba.

741
00:32:15,694 --> 00:32:17,194
Clock is ticking, sir.

742
00:32:21,499 --> 00:32:23,897
Somebody get me Premier Khrushchev.

743
00:32:23,902 --> 00:32:25,165
This has to be a mistake.

744
00:32:25,170 --> 00:32:26,633
You wanna negotiate?

745
00:32:26,638 --> 00:32:29,502
They were right about you. You are soft.

746
00:32:29,507 --> 00:32:33,239
Well, if you don't have the guts
to stand up to those Commies,

747
00:32:33,244 --> 00:32:35,342
I guess I'll have to do it myself.

748
00:32:35,347 --> 00:32:38,011
- You take one more step...
- Or what?

749
00:32:38,016 --> 00:32:42,221
<i>♪ ♪</i>

750
00:32:43,655 --> 00:32:45,085
The steel man.

751
00:32:45,090 --> 00:32:46,219
You're damn right.

752
00:32:46,224 --> 00:32:47,887
Look, Jack, I didn't go rogue.

753
00:32:47,892 --> 00:32:51,057
I'm here to protect the
world from guys like him.

754
00:32:51,062 --> 00:32:53,126
I'm guessing your accomplice here

755
00:32:53,131 --> 00:32:54,894
ain't quite so bulletproof.

756
00:32:54,899 --> 00:32:56,396
Come on!

757
00:32:56,401 --> 00:32:59,933
<i>♪ ♪</i>

758
00:32:59,938 --> 00:33:01,868
Boys. Huddle up. Huddle up!

759
00:33:01,873 --> 00:33:05,205
Okay, we gotta get that
nuclear football back, boys.

760
00:33:05,210 --> 00:33:07,304
Hey, Bobby, what was that play we ran

761
00:33:07,309 --> 00:33:09,309
against Dartmouth back in '39?

762
00:33:09,314 --> 00:33:12,178
[WHISPERING INDISTINCTLY]

763
00:33:12,183 --> 00:33:14,280
Guess we don't need you anymore.

764
00:33:14,285 --> 00:33:15,782
Rude.

765
00:33:15,787 --> 00:33:18,451
30 seconds for the
safeties to be released.

766
00:33:18,456 --> 00:33:20,854
All we gotta do is to keep that football

767
00:33:20,859 --> 00:33:23,823
out of the hands of those
lily-livered Harvard boys.

768
00:33:23,828 --> 00:33:25,291
Okay, Crimson on three.

769
00:33:25,296 --> 00:33:27,160
- One, two, three.
- ALL: Crimson!

770
00:33:27,165 --> 00:33:29,996
<i>[EXCITING MUSIC]</i>

771
00:33:30,001 --> 00:33:34,206
<i>♪ ♪</i>

772
00:33:40,178 --> 00:33:42,208
Hike!

773
00:33:42,213 --> 00:33:45,745
[ALL GRUNTING]

774
00:33:45,750 --> 00:33:49,955
<i>♪ ♪</i>

775
00:33:56,828 --> 00:33:58,529
This is fun.

776
00:34:06,004 --> 00:34:08,234
- [BONE CRACKS]
- Oh!

777
00:34:08,239 --> 00:34:10,770
[IN SLOW-MOTION] My back!

778
00:34:10,775 --> 00:34:12,772
[GROANS]

779
00:34:12,777 --> 00:34:13,807
No.

780
00:34:13,812 --> 00:34:18,017
<i>♪ ♪</i>

781
00:34:26,925 --> 00:34:30,627
[GRUNTS]

782
00:34:33,798 --> 00:34:35,094
Intercepted!

783
00:34:35,099 --> 00:34:38,264
<i>[TRIUMPHANT MUSIC]</i>

784
00:34:38,269 --> 00:34:39,365
Whoo!

785
00:34:39,370 --> 00:34:42,735
<i>♪ ♪</i>

786
00:34:42,740 --> 00:34:45,705
To tell you the truth, sir,

787
00:34:45,710 --> 00:34:47,644
this football belongs in your hands.

788
00:34:48,913 --> 00:34:52,282
[TELETYPE CLACKING]

789
00:34:53,785 --> 00:34:56,082
The missile's headed
straight for us, Jack.

790
00:34:56,087 --> 00:34:57,755
It'll be here any second.

791
00:34:59,390 --> 00:35:01,421
The safeties are off.

792
00:35:01,426 --> 00:35:03,356
You still have time to strike back.

793
00:35:03,361 --> 00:35:05,321
This game ain't over yet, Mr. President.

794
00:35:05,326 --> 00:35:07,126
It's not a damn game.

795
00:35:07,131 --> 00:35:08,431
Whoever launched that missile,

796
00:35:08,436 --> 00:35:09,966
for whatever reason, it was a mistake.

797
00:35:09,971 --> 00:35:12,866
You strike back at the Soviets,
they're gonna strike back at us.

798
00:35:12,871 --> 00:35:15,702
That is why it is called
"mutually assured destruction".

799
00:35:15,707 --> 00:35:18,938
Clearly you do not
understand the concept!

800
00:35:18,943 --> 00:35:20,640
Listen, Jack,

801
00:35:20,645 --> 00:35:22,145
just because we're about to die

802
00:35:22,150 --> 00:35:24,611
doesn't mean we take the
whole damn world with us.

803
00:35:24,616 --> 00:35:27,914
<i>[TENSE MUSIC]</i>

804
00:35:27,919 --> 00:35:31,851
<i>♪ ♪</i>

805
00:35:31,856 --> 00:35:33,453
You're right.

806
00:35:33,458 --> 00:35:35,154
I'm spiking this football.

807
00:35:35,159 --> 00:35:38,191
<i>[SOLEMN MUSIC]</i>

808
00:35:38,196 --> 00:35:42,401
<i>♪ ♪</i>

809
00:35:48,940 --> 00:35:49,973
Um...

810
00:35:52,143 --> 00:35:54,974
Are we about to die?

811
00:35:54,979 --> 00:35:56,976
Yeah.

812
00:35:56,981 --> 00:36:00,346
But at least we gave
it the old college try.

813
00:36:00,351 --> 00:36:03,016
Well, I ain't going out without a fight!

814
00:36:03,021 --> 00:36:07,226
<i>♪ ♪</i>

815
00:36:15,133 --> 00:36:18,368
[ROCKETS RUMBLING]

816
00:36:31,683 --> 00:36:34,618
Take that, you Commie bastards!

817
00:36:42,761 --> 00:36:44,757
Um...

818
00:36:44,762 --> 00:36:48,795
think we can let go of our hands?

819
00:36:48,800 --> 00:36:51,464
You did it, Jack! You saved us all!

820
00:36:51,469 --> 00:36:53,232
[LAUGHS]

821
00:36:53,237 --> 00:36:54,968
Luck of the Irish, I guess.

822
00:36:54,973 --> 00:36:57,470
<i>[EXCITING MUSIC]</i>

823
00:36:57,475 --> 00:36:58,771
Come on, buddy. Get in there.

824
00:36:58,776 --> 00:36:59,906
- Yeah.
- No. Yeah?

825
00:36:59,911 --> 00:37:02,241
- Yeah.
- Yeah. Ah! Ah!

826
00:37:02,246 --> 00:37:03,943
[ALL YELLING]

827
00:37:03,948 --> 00:37:05,878
[ALL WHOOPING]

828
00:37:05,883 --> 00:37:07,451
Go, Crimson!

829
00:37:11,423 --> 00:37:13,720
<i>Captain, I'm detecting an unusual level</i>

830
00:37:13,725 --> 00:37:15,926
<i>of radiation on the ship.</i>

831
00:37:18,230 --> 00:37:20,327
Rory.

832
00:37:20,332 --> 00:37:21,561
[ALIEN CHITTERS]

833
00:37:21,566 --> 00:37:23,263
Are you sure it's safe for us

834
00:37:23,268 --> 00:37:25,098
to be carrying plutonium around?

835
00:37:25,103 --> 00:37:26,667
No.

836
00:37:26,672 --> 00:37:27,705
Whoa!

837
00:37:30,108 --> 00:37:31,609
[ALIEN SNARLS NONCHALANTLY]

838
00:37:38,149 --> 00:37:41,685
Oh, uh, this is not how it looks.

839
00:37:43,055 --> 00:37:44,484
I know.

840
00:37:44,489 --> 00:37:46,153
I owe you an apology.

841
00:37:46,158 --> 00:37:49,256
You saved the entire world
from nuclear Armageddon, Rory.

842
00:37:49,261 --> 00:37:52,225
Well, I, uh... I had help.

843
00:37:52,230 --> 00:37:53,664
Yeah.

844
00:37:55,100 --> 00:37:56,697
[ALIEN CHITTERS]

845
00:37:56,702 --> 00:37:58,498
It doesn't say much, does it?

846
00:37:58,503 --> 00:38:01,468
Oh, she does. You'd be surprised.

847
00:38:01,473 --> 00:38:02,736
- Did you say "she"?
- Mm-hmm.

848
00:38:02,741 --> 00:38:05,372
Huh. So what's the plan?

849
00:38:05,377 --> 00:38:06,907
Well, she's hooking some kind

850
00:38:06,912 --> 00:38:09,242
of turbo charger to the Waverider.

851
00:38:09,247 --> 00:38:10,877
Why would she help us?

852
00:38:10,882 --> 00:38:14,181
I promised her I'd
help her find her ship.

853
00:38:14,186 --> 00:38:16,783
Okay. Do you trust her?

854
00:38:16,788 --> 00:38:18,885
No, it's why I'm going alone.

855
00:38:18,890 --> 00:38:21,254
Oh... uh, no. But that...

856
00:38:21,259 --> 00:38:22,289
But no.

857
00:38:22,294 --> 00:38:24,725
You said your job is to protect history.

858
00:38:24,730 --> 00:38:27,360
I also said your job wasn't
to think for yourself,

859
00:38:27,365 --> 00:38:29,429
but had you listened
to any of my orders,

860
00:38:29,434 --> 00:38:32,366
we'd have absolutely no
hope in finding Sara, so I...

861
00:38:32,371 --> 00:38:35,366
<i>[SOFT MUSIC]</i>

862
00:38:35,371 --> 00:38:36,371
<i>♪ ♪</i>

863
00:38:36,375 --> 00:38:38,271
I guess you got this.

864
00:38:38,276 --> 00:38:39,973
Stop saying nice things.

865
00:38:39,978 --> 00:38:44,183
<i>♪ ♪</i>

866
00:38:44,983 --> 00:38:48,048
You just bring me back my girl, okay?

867
00:38:48,053 --> 00:38:50,417
Mm.

868
00:38:50,422 --> 00:38:51,822
Good luck, big guy.

869
00:38:59,931 --> 00:39:02,195
Sorry, what happened to the ship?

870
00:39:02,200 --> 00:39:04,498
It should be somewhere around here.

871
00:39:04,503 --> 00:39:07,033
[SIGHS] God, these shoes are killing me.

872
00:39:07,038 --> 00:39:08,839
And this stupid hair.

873
00:39:13,712 --> 00:39:15,980
I look like her again, don't I?

874
00:39:19,885 --> 00:39:23,487
I hate that I'm a reminder
of everything you lost.

875
00:39:24,723 --> 00:39:27,387
You're not.

876
00:39:27,392 --> 00:39:29,560
I mean, I guess at first.

877
00:39:31,163 --> 00:39:32,596
But now?

878
00:39:34,266 --> 00:39:36,667
Now you just remind me of you.

879
00:39:40,872 --> 00:39:42,903
Wasn't there a Waverider here?

880
00:39:42,908 --> 00:39:44,438
- Hmm.
- Hey.

881
00:39:44,443 --> 00:39:47,440
[GASPS, CLAPS] Well played, gang.

882
00:39:47,445 --> 00:39:49,309
How'd you manage to avert
nuclear Armageddon?

883
00:39:49,314 --> 00:39:51,044
- Sports analogies.
- Hmm.

884
00:39:51,049 --> 00:39:52,379
- Pot gummies.
- Ah.

885
00:39:52,384 --> 00:39:54,048
- Very on brand for both of you.
- Thank you.

886
00:39:54,052 --> 00:39:55,915
Hey, where are Rory and Spooner?

887
00:39:55,920 --> 00:39:57,751
That son of a bitch stole our ship.

888
00:39:57,756 --> 00:40:00,787
- Ah, very on brand, Mick.
- Oh, come on.

889
00:40:00,792 --> 00:40:02,919
You should be thanking him
for stealing the warhead

890
00:40:02,924 --> 00:40:05,124
out of the missile that
Fidel launched on D.C., yes?

891
00:40:05,129 --> 00:40:06,626
- Thanks, Mick.
- Hmm. Oh!

892
00:40:06,631 --> 00:40:07,995
And he made a deal with the alien

893
00:40:08,000 --> 00:40:09,329
to take it to its ship as long as

894
00:40:09,334 --> 00:40:10,663
it took us to Sara.

895
00:40:10,668 --> 00:40:12,033
- So he stole the ship?
- But it's...

896
00:40:12,037 --> 00:40:14,101
Sorry, my phones are on that ship.

897
00:40:14,106 --> 00:40:15,469
So was my...

898
00:40:15,474 --> 00:40:17,137
oh, thank God.

899
00:40:17,142 --> 00:40:19,206
How are we gonna catch aliens now?

900
00:40:19,211 --> 00:40:22,716
So-so-so sorry, where are going to live?

901
00:40:23,415 --> 00:40:25,545
BOTH: Constantine's house.

902
00:40:25,550 --> 00:40:27,747
Sweet. I could use a little R&R.

903
00:40:27,752 --> 00:40:31,117
All of us under the same
roof with John and Astra.

904
00:40:31,122 --> 00:40:33,153
Could be a real bonding experience.

905
00:40:33,158 --> 00:40:34,455
He's gonna hate it. Let's leave.

906
00:40:34,459 --> 00:40:35,889
- Okay.
- Damn.

907
00:40:35,894 --> 00:40:38,358
Rory had the right idea.

908
00:40:38,363 --> 00:40:40,494
Hmm? Hmm?

909
00:40:40,499 --> 00:40:42,696
<i>[MISCHIEVOUS MUSIC]</i>

910
00:40:42,701 --> 00:40:44,231
Nobody wants your drugs!

911
00:40:44,236 --> 00:40:46,137
[SIGHS] Mom.

912
00:40:48,640 --> 00:40:50,103
Listen up.

913
00:40:50,108 --> 00:40:53,640
Before we start this
little journey of ours,

914
00:40:53,645 --> 00:40:55,308
let's get a few things straight.

915
00:40:55,313 --> 00:40:59,112
Keep your slimy tentacles
off my stash, understand?

916
00:40:59,117 --> 00:41:00,814
[ALIEN SNARLS]

917
00:41:00,819 --> 00:41:02,449
That better be a "yes".

918
00:41:02,454 --> 00:41:03,950
- [ALIEN SNARLS]
- Listen.

919
00:41:03,955 --> 00:41:05,685
If you're gonna run your ugly mouth off

920
00:41:05,690 --> 00:41:07,754
this whole trip, we're
gonna have problems.

921
00:41:07,759 --> 00:41:11,964
<i>[TENSE MUSIC]</i>

922
00:41:14,366 --> 00:41:17,130
<i>[MISCHIEVOUS MUSIC]</i>

923
00:41:17,135 --> 00:41:21,334
I was just asking if you had
anything stronger onboard.

924
00:41:21,339 --> 00:41:25,544
<i>♪ ♪</i>

925
00:41:28,914 --> 00:41:30,581
Don't mind if I do.

926
00:41:38,290 --> 00:41:39,590
[SIGHS]

927
00:41:41,259 --> 00:41:43,223
Here's to long journeys.

928
00:41:43,228 --> 00:41:46,828
<i>[EXCITING MUSIC]</i>

929
00:42:09,008 --> 00:42:10,508
<i>Greg, move your head!</i>

